items.name: Christine Alexis
items.description:
📝Biography📝

(generation advice below) 👇

🌟Christine Alexis🌟

whose real name is Lynn Kristina Cancel, was born on July 8, 1987, in San Diego, California. She is an American actress and model of Hispanic descent. Alexis began her career in the adult entertainment industry in 2007 at the age of 20. She started with a shoot for the film studio FM Concepts before working with other studios such as Mega Site Pass, K.A. Pictures, and B.B. Network. She also appeared in X-rated features for notable companies like Vivid, Bang Productions, Pure Play Media, New Sensations, and JM Productions.

Christine Alexis was often cast as a teenager in her movies. She also modeled for FTV photography. Alexis has piercings in her navel, tongue, and both nipples. She retired from the adult film industry in 2011. Apart from her career in the entertainment industry, Christine enjoys traveling, shopping, taking selfies, and surfing the internet. She is also a dog lover.

As of 2023, Christine Alexis's net worth is estimated to be between $1 million and $5 million. However, information about her current activities is not readily available.

💡Generation Advice💡

🔧Prompt and Sampling🔧

  • Most images have been generated with LORA weighted @ .9 - 1.

  • Most samples done with sampling steps ~40.

  • Sometimes to maintain LORA detail it pays to Hires. fix with upscaler set to "none".

🚀Upscaling🚀

  • Sometimes I just send it to Ultimate SD upscale after a quick render and run 2x at a scale of two.

  • Ultimate SD upscale script used @ ~.15 - .4 denoising using 8x NMKD Faces or 4X UltraSharp redraw upscalers.

🗒️Side Notes🗒️

  • The prompts continue to evolve. CyberRealistic/Edge of Realism/Analog Madness are great realism models, but my LORAs seem to work fine with NAI based checkpoints as well. YMMV.

  • Leave a review if you liked using this.

  • Leave a comment if you are having issues getting good output, I'll try to respond.

items.name: Marle Barrock [Reincarnation Colosseum / Tensei Colosseum]
items.description:
Marle Barrock from Reincarnation Colosseum for the approx three people who know who it is. And for the rest - no, you can't fix her.

(LyCORIS version here)

Prompt: 1girl, marle barrock.
Optional prompts: "ringed yellow eyes", "muscular female" and "dark-skinned female"
Standard outfit: bandaged arms, bandaged legs, elbow gloves, thighhighs, tabard, pelvic curtain.
For more prompt tips see the sample images or the zip of training tags.

The dataset for this was rough and I had to do a lot of shenanigans and retraining to get a working LoRA.
Still, it's not perfect, due to the lack of useable images and the weird outfit lacking good tagging it can bleed over but just use the outfit tags in negatives if that happens.
You can also drop "marle barrock" entirely in some cases and still get decent results if the style is doesn't play nice with your model.

The below information is for the first version. 1.1 should be more flexible and easier to work with.

Trained on NAI it gives results closest to the manga, especially when used with "greyscale" and "monochrome". "hatching (texture)" was also autotagged but it's a fairly weak one so don't expect much of it, you probably need to escape the parenthesis for it to work - "hatching \(texture\)"
AOM2 gives as usual a more semi-realistic look, "3D" and "realistic" along with the above tags should bring it a bit closer to the source material though.

Don't forget to review and upload your own images, it's always fun to see what you're creating!

MISC
Trained on NAI. Dataset of 41 images + 3 selfgenned.
All sample images are raw txt2img, slightly cherrypicked, no inpainting done.
Two or three promo art shots shows Marle has dark red/auburn hair and yellow eyes but those wasn't enough to train on so the dataset is entirely in the manga greyscale/monochrome form.
The training was done on a small subset of the artists images, as such the output of this LoRA is not an accurate representation neither in quality or style of the source material. Go support the artist ZUNTA if you want the good stuff.

items.name: DimensionTwist_DEMONIC
items.description:
I assure you that I really enjoyed tuning this model. As someone who loves horror from a young age, I didn't even know that I had been waiting all this time for a tool to appear that would allow me to bring my favorite fantasy beasts to life, but in a special way. The training was done in Dreambooth and used Dreamshaper_5BakedVae. The model was trained as a style, but I used filewords. This allowed me to have the following characters in one model: Demon, Werewolf, Minotaur, Zombie, Alien, Death, Ghost. The best thing about this principle is that you can "fuse" characters and get a unique result. For example, Demon is a separate character, but when you write Demonic Werewolf in the prompt, that's when magic happens. You can see examples of prompts in the pictures I'm sharing.

Trigger words for characters are, in addition to my beloved token ohwx, are the ones I used in filewords:

  • a minotaur with a horned head standing in a dark temple

  • a creepy looking zombie

  • a creepy looking cartoon zombie

  • a demon in a dark hall

  • a demonic looking monster

  • a werewolf, scary looking

  • a demonic werewolf, frightening, menacing look

  • a swamp zombie

  • a skeleton zombie

  • a creepy bald creature, scary looking

  • a sea monster

  • a forest demon

  • a demon alien

  • a demonic alien creature

  • creepy looking alien insect

  • a death

To make this treat even better, I added 0.15_rfktrsDarkdream_v10, and a pinch of rfktrsMysteryCreatures_v10.

You can see the successful fusion of my fantasies and the aesthetics of the respected Mr. https://civitai.com/user/rfktr/models in the images I milked as representative examples.

I'd suggest experimenting with negative prompts - in some cases you can't get a desired picture without them, and in some cases they have the opposite effect.

You can see examples of prompts in the pictures I'm sharing.

Samplers that work best with this model: DPM+SDE KARRAS, DPS FAST, DPM ADAPTIVE

items.name: Filip Hodas Style
items.description:
Filip Hodas is a Czech digital artist known for his captivating and surreal 3D illustrations, often depicting dystopian and post-apocalyptic landscapes.

His style can be described as surreal, vibrant, and highly detailed. Hodas creates immersive and otherworldly environments by combining elements of nature, technology, and pop culture references. He often incorporates decaying structures, overgrown vegetation, and mysterious artifacts to evoke a sense of abandonment and the passage of time.

Hodas' skillful use of lighting and texturing adds depth and realism to his artwork, enhancing the atmospheric quality and creating a sense of believability in these fantastical landscapes. His compositions are meticulously crafted, with a keen eye for balance, perspective, and visual storytelling.

One of Hodas' notable series is his "Pop Culture Dystopia," where he reimagines iconic pop culture characters and symbols in a dilapidated and desolate setting. Through these images, he offers a commentary on the potential consequences of a hyperconnected and consumer-driven society.

His artwork often sparks curiosity and invites viewers to contemplate the relationship between humans, technology, and the environment. Hodas' ability to seamlessly blend digital techniques with imaginative concepts has gained him a significant following and recognition within the digital art community.

Filip Hodas' art serves as a visual exploration of surreal and dystopian landscapes, reflecting on the consequences of human actions and the fragility of our world. His thought-provoking imagery sparks conversations and invites viewers to contemplate the potential futures that lie ahead.

items.name: Eye Direction
items.description:
About this Model

This LyCORIS:Locon model, eyedirectionV1.8, is for orienting the direction of the eye without using the popular keywords "looking away" in the positive prompt. The model changes eye direction while minimizing large head turns. "looking away" is not bad if we want significant head turns, but for subtle turns it is too much for some of our setups.

Overall, if you want control over eye directions, subtle head turns and some facial expressions, without using ControlNet but, through text prompts only, then this model will give you additional utilities. Also, I have tested this with realistic and anime model checkpoints and works well; just adjust the weight till you see results.

How to Apply

Trigger: eyedirection

Settings:

Weight: 0.3 - 0.5 (or more till you see results without image burnouts)

Methods: DPM++ 2M/2Sa/SDE Karras, Euler a (also experiment with other methods)

Steps: 20 - 30 (less steps for portraits and more for full body or highly detailed image)

CFG: 7-14 (more to follow the prompt and less to be randomly creative)

Hires. fix is optional but is also good in fixing pixelation problems.

Positive prompt keyword options (adjust the weight till you see results):

eyes up, eyes down, eyes up left, eyes up right, eyes down left, eyes down right, eyes left, eyes right, looking above, looking below, looking sideways, eyes left looking sideways, eyes right looking sideways, eyes up looking above, eyes down looking below, eyes up right looking above, eyes down right looking below, eyes up left looking above, eyes down left looking below

ex: girl, <lyco:eyedirectionV1.8:0.3>, eyedirection, (eyes down looking below, slender, short hair:1.5), (plain shirt:1.4), (white background:1.3), (solo, portrait:1.2), (best quality, high quality:1.1), ultra detailed 8k cg, realistic

For random eye direction, at least the word "eyes" must be present in the prompt:

ex: girl, <lyco:eyedirectionV1.8:0.3>, eyedirection, (brown eyes, slender, short hair:1.5), (plain shirt:1.4), (white background:1.3), (solo, portrait:1.2), (best quality, high quality:1.1), ultra detailed 8k cg, realistic

Negative prompt:

(eye contact, eye to eye, looking at camera, looks at camera, looking at viewer, looks at viewer:1.5), (worst quality, low quality:1.1), monochrome

Limitations

It will work in models with anime, realistic or photorealism in them, and since this is my very Very VERY first model, there are still room for improvements and upgrades, so expect for next versions. Also, use this model responsibly and within legalities.

items.name: Eunie
items.description:
Eunie LORA, derived largely from screenshots.

These are the tokens used for each outfit during training:

  • casual, leather jacket, jacket bodysuit, belt, sneakers, black choker

  • tank top bodysuit, belt, sneakers, black choker

  • swimsuit, blue bikini bottom, flower bikini, thigh strap, sarong, sandals, white choker

  • cosplay, thigh boots, elbow gloves, ribbed shirt, blue skirt

The bolded tokens are the outfit names. They should be able to reproduce most outfits on their own.

The general character appearance tokens are:

  • eunie, head wings, multicolored eyes or blue eyes, brown hair, medium hair, breast tattoo/(breast tattoo:0.7)

The character name token should be unnecessary if you're using one of the outfit tokens. Multicolored eyes will create eyes closer to their in game shading, while the strength of the tattoo token frequently needs to be reduced if included.
